```

### The aging curve the model learned

Holding everyone else fixed and sweeping age across a grid (partial dependence)
traces out the aging curve the model inferred on its own — a good sanity check
that it learned baseball rather than noise.

```{r aging, fig.height=4.8}
pdp_sample <- X_tr_raw[sample(nrow(X_tr_raw), min(2000, nrow(X_tr_raw))), , drop = FALSE]
age_grid <- 21:40
pdp_age <- sapply(age_grid, function(a) {
  Xtmp <- pdp_sample; Xtmp[, "age"] <- a
  if ("age_sq" %in% colnames(Xtmp)) Xtmp[, "age_sq"] <- a^2
  mean(predict(xgb_fit, Xtmp))
})
pdp_df <- tibble(age = age_grid, proj_ops = pdp_age)

ggplot(pdp_df, aes(age, proj_ops)) +
  geom_line(colour = col_model, linewidth = 1.1) +
  geom_point(colour = col_model, size = 1.6) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = pdp_df$age[which.max(pdp_df$proj_ops)],
             linetype = "dashed", colour = col_accent) +
  annotate("text", x = pdp_df$age[which.max(pdp_df$proj_ops)] + 0.3,
           y = min(pdp_df$proj_ops),
           label = sprintf("modeled peak ~ age %d", pdp_df$age[which.max(pdp_df$proj_ops)]),
           hjust = 0, colour = col_accent, size = 3.5) +
  labs(title = "The aging curve the model learned",
       subtitle = "Partial dependence of projected OPS on age",
       x = "Age", y = "Projected OPS")
```

### SHAP: how each feature moves a projection

```{r shap, fig.height=5}
feat_names <- colnames(X_te_raw)
shap_mat <- predict(xgb_fit, X_te_raw, predcontrib = TRUE)
colnames(shap_mat) <- c(feat_names, "BIAS")
shap_df <- as.data.frame(shap_mat[, feat_names, drop = FALSE])

shap_imp <- tibble(feature = feat_names, mean_abs = colMeans(abs(shap_df))) |>
  arrange(desc(mean_abs))
top_feats <- head(shap_imp$feature, 10)

shap_long <- bind_rows(lapply(top_feats, function(f)
  tibble(feature = f, shap = shap_df[[f]], value = X_te_raw[, f]))) |>
  group_by(feature) |>
  mutate(value_scaled = (value - min(value)) / (max(value) - min(value) + 1e-9)) |>
  ungroup() |>
  mutate(feature = factor(feature, levels = rev(top_feats)))

ggplot(shap_long, aes(x = shap, y = feature, colour = value_scaled)) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, colour = "grey70") +
  geom_jitter(height = 0.22, alpha = 0.35, size = 0.8) +
  scale_colour_gradient(low = "#2C7FB8", high = "#800000",
                        name = "feature value", breaks = c(0, 1),
                        labels = c("low", "high")) +
  labs(title = "SHAP summary",
       subtitle = "Each dot is a test player; x = contribution to projected OPS",
       x = "SHAP value (OPS units)", y = NULL)
```

A single-player view turns the model from a score into an explanation:

```{r shap-one, fig.height=5}
